<section id="practice-quiz" class="new-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-label">TEST YOUR KNOWLEDGE</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Practice <span style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,var(--electric),var(--cyan));-webkit-background-clip:text;-webkit-text-fill-color:transparent;background-clip:text;">Quiz</span></h2>
    <p class="section-sub">8 questions covering core generative AI concepts. Click an answer to reveal the explanation.</p>

    <div class="quiz-scorebar">
      <span class="quiz-score-label">Score</span>
      <span class="quiz-score-val" id="quiz-score">0 / 8</span>
    </div>

    <div class="quiz-container" id="quiz-container">

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="0">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 1 of 8 &middot; GAN Architecture</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Which component of a GAN evaluates whether submitted content is real (from training data) or synthetic (generated)?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Generator</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Discriminator</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Loss Function</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Encoder</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl">The <strong>Discriminator</strong> scrutinizes the Generator's content and provides feedback to the Loss Function, which scores the Generator and guides its next iteration. (Goodfellow et al. 2014 — Generative Adversarial Nets, arXiv:1406.2661)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="1">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 2 of 8 &middot; Latent Space</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What is the primary role of Latent Space in a GAN training loop?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">To store production data for inference</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">To provide creative input to the Generator</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">To evaluate Discriminator accuracy</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">To measure training loss over epochs</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Latent Space</strong> is the compressed mathematical representation from which the Generator draws creative input at each training step. (Goodfellow et al. 2014 — Generative Adversarial Nets)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="2">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 3 of 8 &middot; Transformer Architecture</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Which neural network architecture forms the foundation of Large Language Models and uses attention mechanisms?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">CNN (Convolutional Neural Network)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">GAN (Generative Adversarial Network)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">VAE (Variational Autoencoder)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Transformer</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Transformers</strong> use encoder-decoder layers with self-attention mechanisms to process sequences in parallel — the core contribution of Vaswani et al. 2017 "Attention Is All You Need" (arXiv:1706.03762).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="3">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 4 of 8 &middot; LLM Risks</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What is a "hallucination" in the context of large language models?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">A visualization technique for neural networks</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">When a model generates plausible but factually incorrect content</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">A method for generating synthetic training data</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">An activation function in deep networks</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Hallucination</strong> is a failure mode where LLM output sounds confident and plausible but is factually wrong or invented. Distinct from data bias; a well-documented risk in production LLMs. (Ji et al. 2022 — Survey of Hallucination in Natural Language Generation)</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="4">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 5 of 8 &middot; GAN Training</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Which GAN training failure occurs when the Generator produces only a narrow variety of outputs rather than the full data diversity?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Hallucination</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Data Bias</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Mode Collapse</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Overfitting</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Mode Collapse</strong> — the Generator finds a small set of outputs that consistently fool the Discriminator, stopping exploration of the full output space. A key known failure mode identified in Goodfellow et al. 2014 (arXiv:1406.2661).</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="5">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 6 of 8 &middot; Alignment</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What does RLHF stand for, and which landmark 2022 paper applied it to align large language models with human intent?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Recursive Learning with Human Features — GPT-4 Technical Report</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback — InstructGPT (Ouyang et al. 2022)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Regulated Language via Human Filtering — Constitutional AI (Anthropic 2022)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Residual Learning via Hierarchical Fine-tuning — Scaling Laws (Kaplan 2020)</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback)</strong> was the technique used in InstructGPT (Ouyang et al. 2022, arXiv:2203.02155) to fine-tune GPT-3 to follow instructions. Human raters ranked outputs; those preferences trained a reward model used in PPO-based RL fine-tuning.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="6">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 7 of 8 &middot; Distributed Training</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Which design pattern trains models on distributed local data, sharing only model updates — not raw data — to preserve privacy?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Serverless Data Pipeline</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Distributed Feature Store</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">AI Workload Autoscaling</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Federated Learning</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Federated Learning</strong> (McMahan et al. 2017) enables training on data that cannot be centralized due to privacy or regulations. Each node trains locally and shares only model parameters — never raw data — which are aggregated to update a global model.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="7">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 8 of 8 &middot; Scaling Laws</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Kaplan et al. 2020 (Scaling Laws for Neural Language Models) found that LLM performance scales predictably with which three factors?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Architecture depth, learning rate, and dropout rate</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Model size (parameters), dataset size, and compute budget</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Batch size, optimizer choice, and activation function</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Tokenizer vocabulary, embedding dimensions, and attention heads</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Scaling Laws</strong> (Kaplan et al. 2020, arXiv:2001.08361) showed that language model loss follows a power-law with model size (parameters), dataset size, and compute — spanning 7+ orders of magnitude. Larger models are more sample-efficient, justifying training very large models on modest data.</div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════
