      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e0">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 1 of 8 · Vaswani et al. 2017</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">In what year was "Attention Is All You Need" published, and what key component did it introduce to replace recurrence?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">2015 — LSTM with gating mechanisms</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">2016 — Convolutional sequence models</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">2017 — Self-attention (Transformer architecture)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">2018 — Bidirectional encoders (BERT)</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>2017 — Self-Attention / Transformer.</strong> Vaswani et al. published "Attention Is All You Need" at NeurIPS 2017 (arXiv:1706.03762). The Transformer replaced RNNs and CNNs entirely with multi-head self-attention, enabling full parallelization and long-range dependency modeling. It became the direct foundation of GPT, BERT, T5, and every modern LLM.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e1">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 2 of 8 · Ouyang et al. 2022</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What does RLHF stand for, and what was the surprising core finding of the InstructGPT paper (Ouyang et al. 2022)?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Recursive Language via Human Filtering — scaling always beats alignment</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Residual Learning with Human Feedback — RLHF requires 10B+ parameters to work</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback — the 1.3B RLHF model outperformed the raw 175B GPT-3 in human evaluations</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Regulated Learning via Human Fine-tuning — RLHF eliminates hallucination entirely</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>RLHF = Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback.</strong> Ouyang et al. 2022 (arXiv:2203.02155) found that their 1.3B InstructGPT model fine-tuned with RLHF was <em>preferred by human raters</em> over the raw 175B GPT-3 — 100× fewer parameters outperforming raw scale. Alignment quality matters as much as model size. The direct precursor to ChatGPT.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e2">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 3 of 8 · Goodfellow et al. 2014</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Who published the original GAN paper, and at what institution?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Yann LeCun — Facebook AI Research (FAIR), 2012</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Ian Goodfellow et al. — Université de Montréal, 2014</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Geoffrey Hinton et al. — University of Toronto, 2013</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Ashish Vaswani et al. — Google Brain, 2017</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Ian Goodfellow et al. — Université de Montréal (2014).</strong> "Generative Adversarial Nets" (arXiv:1406.2661) was co-authored with Pouget-Abadie, Mirza, Xu, Warde-Farley, Ozair, Courville, and Yoshua Bengio — all at Montréal. Goodfellow reportedly conceived the adversarial training idea on a single night after a research debate at a bar.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e3">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 4 of 8 · Bai et al. 2022 (Anthropic)</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What does "Constitutional AI" (Anthropic, 2022) mean — and what is its key difference from standard RLHF?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">A legally binding framework AI companies must follow before deployment</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Training an AI exclusively on constitutional and legal documents</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Using a set of principles for an AI to critique and revise its own outputs (RLAIF) — reducing reliance on human feedback labels for harmlessness</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">A constitutional amendment requiring AI registration with governments</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Constitutional AI = principle-guided self-critique (RLAIF).</strong> Bai et al. 2022 (arXiv:2212.08073) used ~10 natural-language principles (a "constitution") to have an AI critique and revise its own outputs. This RLAIF approach trains harmlessness without human labelers rating every response — making alignment scalable. The foundation of how Claude is trained at Anthropic.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e4">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 5 of 8 · Ho et al. 2020</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What is the core mechanism of Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models (Ho et al. 2020)?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">A GAN discriminator guides each denoising step</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">An encoder-decoder compresses images into latent space</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Learning to reverse a Gaussian noise process — starting from pure noise and iteratively denoising to produce realistic images</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Reinforcement learning rewards guide a generator's quality score</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Reversing a noise process.</strong> Ho, Jain &amp; Abbeel (arXiv:2006.11239) trained a neural net to reverse a Markov chain that gradually adds Gaussian noise to data. Key simplification: the training objective reduces to predicting the noise added at each step — equivalent to denoising score matching. Achieved FID 3.17 on CIFAR-10. Foundation of Stable Diffusion, DALL-E 2, and Midjourney.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e5">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 6 of 8 · Kaplan et al. 2020</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">Scaling Laws (Kaplan et al. 2020) found LLM performance scales predictably with which three factors?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Learning rate, batch size, and dropout rate</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">Model size (N parameters), dataset size (D tokens), and compute budget (C FLOPs)</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Number of attention heads, embedding dimensions, and vocabulary size</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Number of layers, layer width, and activation function</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>N (parameters), D (tokens), C (compute).</strong> Kaplan et al. 2020 (arXiv:2001.08361) showed test loss scales as power laws with these three quantities over 7+ orders of magnitude. Architectural choices (depth vs. width, attention heads) matter far less within a wide range. Key implication: larger models are more sample-efficient — justifying the push to train enormous models.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e6">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 7 of 8 · Brown et al. 2020</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">What is "in-context learning" as demonstrated by GPT-3 (Brown et al. 2020)?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Fine-tuning the model on new data collected from user conversations</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">An attention mechanism that reads from external memory banks at inference</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">The model performs new tasks from examples in the prompt with no gradient updates — task learning via attention over the context window</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">Retrieval-augmented generation from an external search index</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>In-context learning = task adaptation via the prompt, no gradient updates.</strong> Brown et al. (arXiv:2005.14165) showed GPT-3 could learn to do translation, arithmetic, or code generation from just a few in-context examples. The model "learns" from examples within a single forward pass — demonstrating emergent generalization that made prompting a new programming paradigm.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="quiz-q" data-qid="e7">
        <div class="quiz-qnum">Question 8 of 8 · Vaswani et al. 2017</div>
        <div class="quiz-qtext">The self-attention formula divides by √dₖ: Attention(Q,K,V) = softmax(QKᵀ / √dₖ)·V. Why?</div>
        <div class="quiz-opts">
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">To normalize output embeddings to unit length</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="true">To prevent dot products from growing large in high dimensions, which pushes softmax into near-zero gradient regions</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">To scale the learning rate proportionally to key dimension</button>
          <button class="quiz-opt" data-correct="false">To reduce memory usage by compressing the attention matrix</button>
        </div>
        <div class="quiz-expl"><strong>Gradient stability — preventing softmax saturation.</strong> Vaswani et al. (arXiv:1706.03762) noted that in high-dimensional spaces, dot products grow large in magnitude, pushing softmax into regions with extremely small gradients — making learning slow or impossible. Dividing by √dₖ keeps dot products in a well-behaved range. A small but crucial detail enabling stable Transformer training at scale.</div>
      </div>

